        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       Fighting food waste with "magic bags" 
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
              
         These days, the frustrating truth about bakeries, cafés, restaurants, and supermarkets is that they regularly <strong>toss out food simply because it didn’t sell in time</strong>. This is not just wasteful, but is turning into a full-blown environmental crisis. 

          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/too-good-to-go-grocery-bag.jpg" alt="A paper bag with the Too Good To Go logo placed on a store counter." href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
           Too Good To Go stepped in as a bridge between food businesses with surplus and people who’d happily eat discounted food, and in doing so, it became a movement. Source: notizieplus</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Globally, the UN World Food Programme estimates that a staggering <strong>$1 trillion worth of food is wasted every year</strong>. That’s enough to feed two billion people and slash over 3.3 billion tons of greenhouse gases from the atmosphere. 
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>And for co-founder Jamie Crummie, it was personal</strong>. As a teenager working in supermarkets and later in hospitality gigs across Australia, he witnessed firsthand just how much edible food ended up in the trash. But the real turning point was in 2013 when Jamie attended an event catered entirely with “rescued” food, meals that had been diverted from the trash. 
            </p>
             <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           That moment planted the seed. A few years later, in Copenhagen, he teamed up with other like-minded entrepreneurs, and <strong><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-5-jul-25-tpodg-h1-1-too-good-to-go" target="_blank">Too Good To Go </a>was born</strong>.
            </p>
             <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           The premise is that <strong>users get “magic bags” of surplus food from local businesses, sold at steep discounts, typically 50%–70% lower</strong>. You won’t know exactly what’s in your bag, only the type. A Starbucks magic bag might get you a mix of baked goods; a sushi shop might pack in leftover rolls. 
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          They've <strong>rescued over 200 million meals</strong> and have <strong>earned approximately $162M to date</strong>. As of mid-2025, Too Good To Go has over 100 million users and operates in 19 countries, partnering with more than 150,000 businesses, including big names like Starbucks, Aldi, Carrefour, Costa, and Morrisons. 
            </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>


