  <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="0px">
      <mj-column>
       <mj-spacer height="18px"></mj-spacer>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       Cracking the coconut market
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      It all started on a chilly New York night in 2003, when two men, <strong>Michael Kirban and Ira Liran</strong>, met two Brazilian women at a bar. During their conversation, the women casually mentioned how much they missed coconut water from home. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     Nothing came of it then, but that passing comment would spark the birth of <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-5-jul-25-tpodg-h2-2-vita-coco" target="_blank">Vita Coco</a>, currently the <strong>world’s best-selling coconut water brand valued at over $1.1B</strong>.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/vita-coco-coconut-water-flavors.jpg" alt="Four different Vita Coco coconut water cartons lined up on a table." href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
           Vita Coco championed sustainable packaging, partnered with Roblox and DoorDash for “cool” campaigns, and still keeps innovating. Source: Vita Coco via Fooddive</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           The idea truly took root months later when Kirban visited his friend and future co-founder Liran, who, by the way, had followed one of those women all the way to Brazil. Once there, they saw <strong>coconut water everywhere. It was a way of life</strong>. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        And it dawned on them that this wildly popular tropical beverage was <strong>unknown in the US</strong>, even as Americans were getting hooked on wellness trends like yoga, Pilates, keto, and green juice cleanses.
          </p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       They struck an agreement with a Brazilian supplier and scraped together $75,000, mostly from Kirban’s pocket money he’d earned from a real estate software startup (which he still helps run). But when their first shipment arrived in NYC, it got stuck at the border. <strong>They hadn’t registered it with the FDA</strong>. The cargo was rerouted to the Bahamas, where they ended up selling it door to door, at bars, grocery stores, and even people’s homes, barely breaking even.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       To stay afloat, Kirban turned to a creative strategy that was equal parts genius and madness. He began <strong>opening zero-interest cards, transferring the balance from one to the next, effectively buying time</strong>. He kept doing it, stacking card on card, pushing repayments as far down the road as possible, and helping them delay giving up equity too early.
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       Eventually, they did raise outside funding. The first one came in 2007 from the Belgian firm Verlinvest, followed by a <strong>celeb-studded funding round led by Madonna</strong>, and later by Keurig Dr Pepper. In October 2021, they went public. Since then, <strong>Vita Coco’s stock has surged 300% from post-IPO lows</strong>, and these days, it serves over 100 million customers worldwide.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="4px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       The bath bomb revolution
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      If you’ve ever wandered past a Lush store, chances are <strong>you smelled it before you saw it</strong>. That unmistakable scent has been luring in ethically-minded bathers since 1995.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/lush-handmade-cosmetics-packaging.jpg" alt="Person wearing a LUSH Fresh Handmade Cosmetics shirt holding a black container of Lush product." href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            Everything in Lush is handmade, and each product comes labeled with a sticker showing the face of the employee who made it. Source: Getty Images via Allure</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          It all began with <strong>Mark Constantine</strong>, a hair specialist, with a hankering for natural beauty. In the 1970s, <strong>Constantine and his partner, Liz Weir</strong>, started supplying homemade, ethically sourced beauty products to a then-up-and-coming brand, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-5-jul-25-tpodg-h3-3-the-body-shop" target="_blank">The Body Shop</a>. That worked great, until <strong>The Body Shop bought their formulas</strong> and cut ties.
            </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      But Constantin, along with a tight-knit team of co-founders, many of whom still co-own the business to this day, regrouped. In 1995, <strong><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-5-jul-25-tpodg-h3-4-lush" target="_blank">Lush</a> was born</strong> in Poole, England, <strong>part protest and part passion project</strong>.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     Where the industry was full of plastic packaging, synthetic fragrances, and animal testing, Lush leaned in the opposite direction with <strong>cruelty-free, handmade, vegetarian, and 80% vegan, fresh-from-the-farm skincare</strong>. The products use ingredients from around the world, including fresh produce purchased from local farms. They also made the <Strong>smart move to keep it all in-house</strong> and not outsource to giant factories. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     By 1996, Lush expanded into North America, setting up shop and factories in Vancouver and Toronto. They’ve since gone global, but their punk ethos remains intact. They <strong>still refuse to advertise conventionally</strong>, and instead funnel that money into activism, sustainable sourcing, and bold political stances. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
    Lush has <strong>donated over $17M</strong> to more than 1,400 grassroots organizations. And they’ve found clever ways to pull customers into the mission, like the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-5-jul-25-tpodg-h3-5-black-pot-program" target="_blank">Black Pot Program</a>, for example. Return five empty containers, and you get a complimentary face mask honing on loyalty, sustainability, and skincare all in one.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
    Lush is still privately owned, and while they don’t disclose exact revenue, estimates suggest annual revenue in the hundreds of millions. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
